			  	It's working now.  I'm recovering ships I lost to this bug by using the exploit to this bug.  This seems like the kind of exploit that the Koreans or TE would use.<br />
<br />
At any rate, I'm not nulling the server, I'm just biding my time until a null happens and making sure that my fleet is set up to benefit from the occurance.<br />
<br />
BTW - It only happens on nulls that actually roll back the events of the turn.<br />
<br />
***EDIT***<br />
<br />
I got my fleets back, but you won't believe how tempting it was to just keep on going.  Please, please, make this a priority.  I know that most people will not be able to resist.<br />
<br />
And for the players that haven't figured it out yet, if you are just starting out and got a cool design off of the Black Market that you can't build, this is the way to replicate it.<br />
<br />
Fix this exploit please.<br />
<br />
<br />
EXTRA INFORMATION<br />
<br />
It seems as if reductions to the ship pool are immediately committed to the Database (I'm not a dbm so please forgive me if I get the terminology wrong) as well as increases.  But the fleets not in the pool are not committed right away but only at the end of a turn.  I'm sure that this is the result of some other exploit, but I wonder why ALL changes aren't either committed on the fly (server resource constraints?) or at the end of the turn.  I would prefer on the fly to avoid roll-backs when someone doesn't like the way a battle went (like Koreans a few sets back, and other players that we don't know about).			   <P align=right></P>
